ce:section.ce:para:
The feasibility of SA/CNF-based composite film as smart freshness preservation film was verified using shrimp. Fresh shrimps were refrigerated for 15 days, and the pH, TVC, TBARS, and firmness values of the shrimp were measured every 5 days to evaluate the correlation between quality parameters and film response (
                           Fig. 8

                           ). Polyethylene, SA/CNF, and SA/CNF/CD films did not show any noticeable color change during the shrimp spoilage process. In addition, the red color of shrimp samples stored in PE and SA/CNF films shows that the shrimp color changed from gray to orange/red after 5 days of storage, indicating that the spoilage process began. For the samples labeled with SA/CNF/CD film, the color change of shrimp was noticeable on the 15th day, confirming the presence of CDs could extend the shelf life of shrimp by imparting antioxidant and antibacterial abilities. The green SA/CNF/PANI film started to change color after 10 days and turned blue within 15 days of storage, reflecting that the shrimp samples labeled with SA/CNF/PANI film had deteriorated and produced volatile amine compounds. Therefore, the color change of the shrimp to red showed a steep slope from the 10th day. However, the color of the SA/CNF/CD@PANI label did not show significant color change during the 10-day storage of shrimp at 4 °C, indicating that the shrimp was still fresh. When the storage period changed from 10 to 15 days, the color of the film changed slightly, indicating that shrimp began to deteriorate. Therefore, the color change of shrimp samples stored in the SA/CNF/CD@PANI film was less than that of other samples, confirming that the film has a positive potential to maintain the freshness of food.
